  volume    =  237,
  number    =  7,
  pages     = "1767--1779",
  abstract  = "A radiation-induced mouse mutant, Brachyrrhine (Br), exhibits
               frontonasal dysplasia and renal hypoplasia, two malformations
               associated with deficiencies in mesenchymal condensation. The
               purpose of this study was to resolve the Br locus, evaluate
               possible candidate genes, and identify developmental defects in
               the mutant chondrocranium. Linkage analysis mapped the Br
               mutation to a critical region distal to D17Mit76, which contains
               only one gene, the transcription factor Six2. Sequence analysis
               of the Six2 gene, including 1.5 kb of the promoter, failed to
               reveal the Br mutation. However, homozygous Br/Br embryos showed
               almost complete absence of Six2 mRNA and protein in craniofacial
               and renal tissues while heterozygous Br/+ embryos displayed
               intermediate Six2 levels. Mutant embryos displayed malformations
               of neural crest-derived structures of the anterior cranium where
               Six2 is normally expressed. These data suggest a mutation in a
