@ARTICLE{Janssen2023-vz,
  title     = "The effect of background noise and its removal on the analysis of
               single-cell expression data",
  author    = "Janssen, Philipp and Kliesmete, Zane and Vieth, Beate and
               Adiconis, Xian and Simmons, Sean and Marshall, Jamie and McCabe,
               Cristin and Heyn, Holger and Levin, Joshua Z and Enard, Wolfgang
               and Hellmann, Ines",
  journal   = "Genome Biol.",
  publisher = "BioMed Central",
  volume    =  24,
  number    =  1,
  pages     =  140,
  abstract  = "BACKGROUND: In droplet-based single-cell and single-nucleus
               RNA-seq experiments, not all reads associated with one cell
               barcode originate from the encapsulated cell. Such background
               noise is attributed to spillage from cell-free ambient RNA or
               barcode swapping events. RESULTS: Here, we characterize this
               background noise exemplified by three scRNA-seq and two snRNA-seq
               replicates of mouse kidneys. For each experiment, cells from two
               mouse subspecies are pooled, allowing to identify cross-genotype
               contaminating molecules and thus profile background noise.
               Background noise is highly variable across replicates and cells,
               making up on average 3-35\% of the total counts (UMIs) per cell
               and we find that noise levels are directly proportional to the
               specificity and detectability of marker genes. In search of the
               source of background noise, we find multiple lines of evidence
               that the majority of background molecules originates from ambient
               RNA. Finally, we use our genotype-based estimates to evaluate the
               performance of three methods (CellBender, DecontX, SoupX) that
               are designed to quantify and remove background noise. We find
               that CellBender provides the most precise estimates of background
               noise levels and also yields the highest improvement for marker
               gene detection. By contrast, clustering and classification of
               cells are fairly robust towards background noise and only small
               improvements can be achieved by background removal that may come
               at the cost of distortions in fine structure. CONCLUSIONS: Our
               findings help to better understand the extent, sources and impact
               of background noise in single-cell experiments and provide
               guidance on how to deal with it.",
  month     =  jun,
  year      =  2023,
  keywords  = "(Gold) standard scRNA-seq data set; Ambient RNA; Background
               noise; Barcode swapping; Correction method comparison;
               Single-cell RNA-sequencing",
  language  = "en"
